<h2 id="how-to-properly-indent-and-space-html">How to Properly Indent and Space HTML</h2>

<p>In <abbr title="Hyper Text Markup Language">HTML</abbr>, the beginning and ending tags of an element on multiple lines should always be left-aligned. For example, when you see <code class="highlight__code">&lt;div&gt;</code>, you should be able to visually scan the page straight down to find its closing tag (the same for <code class="highlight__code">&lt;header&gt;</code>, <code class="highlight__code">&lt;main&gt;</code> and <code class="highlight__code">&lt;footer&gt;</code>). One way to implement this is to create opening and closing tags at the same time and then add the contents.</p>

<p>When elements are nested within another element, they should be indented two or four spaces from the opening tag. For example, I chose to indent my HTML with two spaces. <code class="highlight__code">&lt;header&gt;</code> is indented two spaces from <code class="highlight__code">&lt;div&gt;</code>, and <code class="highlight__code">&lt;h1&gt;</code> is indented two spaces from <code class="highlight__code">&lt;header&gt;</code>. Make sure that your <abbr title="Hyper Text Markup Language">HTML</abbr> indenting is consistent throughout the page.</p>

<p>You might be wondering why I chose to not indent <code class="highlight__code">&lt;head&gt;</code> and <code class="highlight__code">&lt;body&gt;</code> in the <code class="highlight__code">&lt;html&gt;</code> tag. I like to keep it un-indented because there should only be 2 nested elements in <code class="highlight__code">&lt;html&gt;</code> and I think its unnessecary to have it indented. You could indent it if you want.</p>

<p>If you use the tab key to space over, make sure it is set to your chosen spacing. Also, notice that there is no space between the text content of an element and its tags, <strong>if</strong> it takes a single line. For example, <code class="highlight__code">&lt;h1&gt;Wow header&lt;/h1&gt;</code> has no spaces between <code class="highlight__code">&lt;h1&gt;</code> and the word â€˜Wowâ€™. If a tag has multiline text you could choose to indent it with a new line so it is spaced nicely, but it is not neccessary if it isnâ€™t possible (ie: itâ€™s pasted content). A fix to this is having the pasted text indented two spaces from the opening tag like with <code class="highlight__code">&lt;div&gt;</code> and <code class="highlight__code">&lt;header&gt;</code>.</p>

<h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>

<p>Regardless of the language you use to write code, learn the indentation and spacing standards for it.</p>

<p>In HTML:</p>

<ul>
  <li>the beginning and ending tags of an element on multiple lines should always be left-aligned.</li>
  <li>When elements are nested within another element, they should be indented two or four spaces from the opening tag.</li>
  <li>If you use the tab key to space over, make sure it is set to your chosen spacing.</li>
  <li>If a tag takes a single line of text, there should be no space between the text content of an element and its tags.</li>
  <li>If a tag has multiline text, you could choose to indent it with a new line so it is spaced nicely, but it is not neccessary if it isnâ€™t possible (ie: itâ€™s pasted content).</li>
</ul>

<p>Practice consistency so that your code is easily readable to other coders as well as your future self.</p>
